shortDefinitions: make choice from range of possibilities

etymologies: early 17th century: from Latin stipulat- ‘demanded as a formal promise’, from the verb stipulari

definitions: demand or specify (a requirement), typically as part of an agreement

examples.text: he stipulated certain conditions before their marriage

etymologies: late 18th century: from Latin stipula (see stipule) + -ate

definitions: (of a leaf or plant) having stipules.

etymologies: late Middle English (in the sense ‘pull up by the roots’): from Latin eradicat- ‘torn up by the roots’, from the verb eradicare, from e- (variant of ex-) ‘out’ + radix, radic- ‘root’

definitions: destroy completely; put an end to

examples.text: this disease has been eradicated from the world
